1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,000
One IP, multiple services, different domains, that's what Ingress does.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:14,240
Every service as a load balancer means a separate IP and a separate cloud bill.

3
00:00:14,240 --> 00:00:17,680
Node port works, but port numbers are ugly.

4
00:00:17,680 --> 00:00:22,240
Ingress is one entry point that routes by hostname and path.

5
00:00:22,240 --> 00:00:26,040
You define an Ingress resource with routing rules.

6
00:00:26,040 --> 00:00:33,200
An Ingress controller, EngineX, Trific, HAProxy, reads those rules and acts on them.

7
00:00:33,200 --> 00:00:37,640
Traffic flows, internet to controller to service to pods.

8
00:00:37,640 --> 00:00:43,800
Route by hostname, api.example.com goes to the API service.

9
00:00:43,800 --> 00:00:47,600
App.example.com goes to the front end.

10
00:00:47,600 --> 00:00:52,960
Route by path, slash api slash routes differently than slash app slash.

11
00:00:52,960 --> 00:00:56,520
TLS termination happens at the controller.

12
00:00:56,520 --> 00:01:00,440
Your services stay plain HTTP internally.

13
00:01:00,440 --> 00:01:03,640
One catch, the Ingress API is frozen.

14
00:01:03,640 --> 00:01:05,040
No new features.

15
00:01:05,040 --> 00:01:08,640
For new projects, look at Gateway API instead.

16
00:01:08,640 --> 00:01:11,520
Run the docs, Kubernetes, Ingress.

